          "title": "Python Syntax and Structure",
          "content": "### ğŸ“ Python Syntax and Structure\n\n### ğŸ“‹ Comprehensive Guide to Python Code Organization\n\n**Key Terms:**\n- **Indentation**: Whitespace at the beginning of lines to show code structure\n- **Code Block**: Group of statements executed together\n- **Syntax**: Rules governing code structure and format\n- **Comment**: Non-executable text for documentation\n- **Statement**: Complete instruction in Python\n\n### ğŸ“ Section 1: Indentation System - Definition and Rules\n\n**Definition**: Python uses indentation (spaces or tabs) instead of braces `{}` to define code blocks and hierarchy.\n\n**Core Indentation Rules:**\n1. **Standard Practice**: Use exactly 4 spaces per indentation level\n2. **Consistency Requirement**: All lines at same level must have identical indentation\n3. **Nesting Rule**: Each nested level adds one more indentation (4 more spaces)\n4. **Error Prevention**: Never mix spaces and tabs in the same file\n5. **Mandatory Rule**: Code blocks following colons (`:`) must be indented\n\n**Correct Indentation Examples:**\n```python\nif condition:                    # Level 0 (no indentation)\n    statement1                   # Level 1 (4 spaces)\n    statement2                   # Level 1 (4 spaces)\n    if nested_condition:         # Level 1 (4 spaces)\n        nested_statement         # Level 2 (8 spaces)\n```\n\n**Common Indentation Errors:**\n- `IndentationError`: Missing indentation after colon\n- `IndentationError`: Inconsistent indentation within same block\n- `TabError`: Mixing tabs and spaces\n\n### ğŸ“‹ Section 2: Comment Documentation Standards\n\n**Comment Types and Usage:**\n\n1. **Single-line Comments**\n   - Syntax: `# comment text`\n   - Purpose: Brief explanations or notes\n   - Placement: Above code line or at end of line\n\n2. **End-of-line Comments**\n   - Syntax: `code  # explanation`\n   - Purpose: Immediate clarification\n   - Best Practice: At least 2 spaces before `#`\n\n3. **Multi-line Comments (Docstrings)**\n   - Syntax: `\"\"\"comment block\"\"\"`\n   - Purpose: Detailed documentation\n   - Usage: Function/class documentation, complex explanations\n\n**Comment Writing Guidelines:**\n- Explain WHY, not WHAT the code does\n- Keep comments current with code changes\n- Use TODO comments for future improvements\n- Avoid obvious comments (`x = 5  # set x to 5`)\n\n### ğŸ“ Section 3: Code Organization Principles\n\n**Line Continuation Methods:**\n\n1. **Parentheses Method (Preferred)**\n   ```python\n   result = (expression1 +\n             expression2 +\n             expression3)\n   ```\n\n2. **Backslash Method**\n   ```python\n   text = \"string part 1\" \\\n          \"string part 2\"\n   ```\n\n**Statement Organization Rules:**\n- **Preferred**: One statement per line\n- **Acceptable**: Multiple simple statements with semicolons\n- **Line Length**: Maximum 79 characters (PEP 8 standard)\n- **Blank Lines**: Use to separate logical sections\n\n### ğŸ“‹ Code Quality Checklist\n\n**Before Submitting Code, Verify:**\n- [ ] Consistent 4-space indentation throughout\n- [ ] No mixing of tabs and spaces\n- [ ] Comments explain complex logic\n- [ ] Line length under 80 characters\n- [ ] Blank lines separate different sections\n- [ ] No trailing whitespace\n- [ ] Proper nesting levels maintained\n\n**Summary Points:**\n1. Python's indentation system replaces braces for code structure\n2. Four spaces per level is the standard indentation\n3. Comments should explain reasoning, not obvious actions\n4. Code organization improves readability and maintenance\n5. Consistency in style is more important than personal preference\n\n**Note-Taking Template:**\n```\nTopic: Python Indentation\nRule: ________________\nExample: _____________\nCommon Error: ________\nSolution: ____________\n```"
